Explain the difference between deep copy and shallow copy.
Shallow Copy:
exp: if change one place that thing reflect into another place
import copy  

a = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]

# Creating a shallow copy of the nested list 'original'
b = copy.copy(a)

# Modifying an element in the shallow-copied list
b[0][0] = 99

# Printing the original and shallow-copied lists  
print("b: ", b) 
print("a: ", a)

Creates a new object, but inserts references to the existing objects found in the original.

Changes made to the nested objects in the copy will reflect in the original object, and vice versa.

This is because both objects are pointing to the same memory location for the nested objects.

Shallow copy is faster and consumes less memory than deep copy.


Deep Copy: if i'll change one new place that will not reflect into original list
syntax: copy.deepcopy()
import copy

a = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]

# Creating a deep copy of the nested list 'a'
b = copy.deepcopy(a)

# Modifying an element in the deep-copied list
b[0][0] = 99 
print("b: ", b) 
print("a: ", a) 

Creates a completely independent copy of the original object and all its nested objects.

Changes made to the copy or the original object will not affect each other.

This is because each object has its own separate copy of the data.

Deep copy is slower and consumes more memory, especially for large and complex data structures.
