What is the difference between __init__ and __new__ methods?
In Python, the __new__ method creates a new object instance, while the __init__ method initializes the attributes of that new object. __new__ is called before __init__.
__new__
is a static method that allocates memory and prepares the object. It's responsible for returning a new instance of the class. __new__ can return any object.
__init__
is an instance method that initializes the state of the newly created object. It receives the argument self, which represents the instance of a class. __init__ must return None

