What is the difference between __str__ and __repr__ methods in Python?
In Python, the __str__ and __repr__ methods are used to define string representations of objects. They serve different purposes and have different intended audiences.

__str__ Method

Purpose: Provides a "nice" or "informal" string representation of an object, which is meant to be readable.



class Person:
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
    def __str__(self):
        return f"{self.name}, {self.age} years old"
p = Person("Alice", 30)
print(str(p))  # Output: Alice, 30 years old
print(p)       # Output: Alice, 30 years old

-----------------
__repr__ Method
Purpose: Provides an "official" string representation of an object, which is meant to be unambiguous and ideally, complete enough to recreate the object.



class Person:
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
    def __repr__(self):
        return f"Person(name={self.name!r}, age={self.age})"
p = Person("Alice", 30)
print(repr(p))  # Output: Person(name='Alice', age=30)
